Please cite this article in press as: T. Dehoux et al., Probing single-cell mechanics with picosecond ultrasonics, Ultrasonics (2014), http://dx.doi.org/ 10.1016/j.ultras.2014.07.010


As expected, Xt ! Xb when d ! 0. We plot with a dotted line Xb vs frequency in Fig. 5 for a Ti film of thickness 500 nm deposited on Al2O3 (see Table 1). At frequencies below a critical frequency fc 1 , indicated by the vertical dotted line, the diffusion length in Ti is greater than the film thickness, g1d 1. In this case Xb 1⁄4 Xt, meaning that thermal confinement occurs in the Ti layer. Beyond fc, Xt Xb and the temperature rise at the Ti-substrate interface does not reach the top Ti surface where the cells are deposited. In the remainder, we therefore choose fm 1⁄4 1 MHz to limit thermal confinement while keeping a good signal-to-noise ratio. The analytical modeling has thus allowed us to optimize the design of the transducer (thickness, substrate diffusivity and modulation frequency) to reduce temperature rise at the cell-transducer interface.
3.2. Simultaneous probing of the density and compressibility of an Allium cepa cell
We now use the opto-acoustic bio-transducer described above to measure simultaneously the acoustic reflection coefficient and the Brillouin oscillations. We applied this procedure to determine both the density and compressibility of a single Alium cepa cell. Since such cells withstand higher fluences than animal cells do, we used a SiO2 substrate as a cheap alternative to Al2O3. We deposited a 500 nm thick polycrystalline titanium film on a SiO2 substrate by RF sputtering. The pump was focused at the bottom of the Ti film to reduce thermal stress to the cell, and the probe beam was focused on the top surface of the transducer, through the cell
(see Fig. 2). To characterize the bandwidth of the transducer, we plot in Fig. 6(a) the reflectivity change dR measured on the bare transducer. No transient-temperature rise is observed, indicating that the thermal diffusion length at the laser repetition frequency fr is smaller than the Ti film thickness. Due to the relatively low acoustic mismatch at the Ti–SiO2 interface (acoustic reflection coefficient Rts 1⁄4 0:22), the thermoelastic generation at the Ti–SiO2 interface launches almost unipolar strain pulses in the Ti film and in the SiO2 substrate [77]. The unipolar pulse propagating in Ti is detected as a bipolar echo, at times 140 and 290 ps due to the successive reflections at the film interfaces. The amplitude of the Fourier spectrum of the echoes plotted in the inset of Fig. 6(a) reveals a broad frequency bandwidth centered around 50 GHz, and extending up to 120 GHz. We extracted the amplitudes of the echoes using a wavelet analysis at a given frequency. We used a Morlet wavelet defined by
WmðtÞ 1⁄4 cosð4atÞ exp1⁄2 ðatÞ2=2 ð7Þ
where the scaling factor a controls the center frequency of the wavelet fw. For more accurate results, we chose a 50 GHz wavelet located at the center of the acoustic bandwidth [see dotted line in the inset of Fig. 6(a)]. The convolution of the transient dR measured on the bare transducer with the wavelet is plotted in Fig. 7 with a plain line. The first two echoes are clearly visible. The ratio of the second to the first echo yields the acoustic reflection coefficient Rts 1⁄4 ðZt ZsÞ=ðZt þ ZsÞ 1⁄4 0:22 at the Ti–SiO2 interface, where Zt and Zs are the acoustic impedances of Ti and SiO2, respectively. The longitudinal sound velocity in SiO2 vs 1⁄4 5790 m s 1 was determined from the Brillouin frequency (measured separately [24], not shown), and from the refractive index ns 1⁄4 1:45. The acoustic impedance of SiO2 is therefore Zs 1⁄4 qsvs 1⁄4 12:7 MPa s m 1, where
qs 1⁄4 2:2 g cm 3 is the mass density. Based on this value, the imped
ance of the Ti film Zt 1⁄4 19:5 MPa s m 1 can be deduced from Rts. We plot in Fig. 6(b) the reflectivity change dR measured when a single Allium cepa cell is placed on the top surface of the transducer. In this case we observe Brillouin oscillations at a frequency of 5:6 0:1 GHz in the vacuole. Using the refractive index of the cell nv 1⁄4 1:35 [47], we obtain the sound velocity in the cell
